These are fair points. As a general rule, you shouldn't ever need to disable a linter error when you own the code end to end. In our codebase, the vast majority of disabled lint errors exist to access private or undocumented members of a class whose code we can't refactor (normally external dependencies). The rest exist to interop with code that doesn't follow our style guides.

